<module status="bronze">
  <h>gu</h>
  <p><g>gu</g>
    <en>to, until, till, unto, for</en> is the (non-leniting) allative <a
      href="?xx=prepositions/prepositions">preposition</a>.</p>
  <p>The allative preposition should not be confused with other uses of the particle <a
      href="?gd=gu"><g>gu</g></a>.</p>
  <section>
    <h>forms</h>
    <section id="indefinite">
      <h>indefinite</h>
      <p>The default form of the allative preposition is simply <g>gu</g> – <ul>
          <li><m>gu</m> doras <en>to a door</en></li>
          <li><m>gu</m> eileanan <en>to islands</en></li>
          <li><m>gu</m> Tormod <en>to Norman</en></li>
          <li><m>gu</m> trì craobhan <en>to three trees</en></li>
        </ul></p>
    </section>
    <section id="definite">
      <h>definite</h>
      <p>When the immediately following word is a form of the definite article, the form <g>gus</g>
        is used instead – <ul>
          <li><m>gus an</m> doras <en>to the door</en></li>
          <li><m>gus a’</m> bhalach <en>to the boy</en></li>
          <li><m>gus na h-</m>eileanan <en>to the islands</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <!-- <p><g>gus</g> is also used before certain other phrases starting with the particle <g>a</g>
        (e.g. <g>gus a-màireach</g>
        <en>till tomorrow</en>, <g>gus a h-uile duine</g>
        <en>to everyone</en>, and in prepositional relative clauses – an duine <g>gus an do
          chuir</g> i an leabhar <en>the man to whom she sent the book</en>.</p>-->
      <!-- <p>Note also that, in particular (spatial?) senses (see below), the preposition form
          <g>gus</g> is <emph>not</emph> used before a definite article. Rather, the
        pseudo-preposition <a href="?gd=chun">chun</a> is used instead.</p> -->
      <p>Fused forms are occasionally found when the immediately following word is
        a <!--<a href="?xx=nouns/possessive_determiners">possessive determiner</a>-->
        possessive determiner – <ul>
          <li><m>gu mo</m> thaigh <en>to my house</en> ≈ <g>gum</g> thaigh</li>
          <li><m>gu do</m> bhaile <en>to your town</en> ≈ <g>gud</g> bhaile</li>
          <li><m>gu a h-</m>eaglais <en>to her church</en> ≈ <g>ga h-</g>eaglais</li>
          <li>
            <m>gu a</m> chraoibh <en>to his tree</en> ≈ <g>ga</g> chraoibh</li>
          <li><m>gu ar n-</m>achadh <en>to our field</en> ≈ <g>gar n-</g>achadh</li>
          <li><m>gu ur</m> leapannan <en>to your beds</en> ≈ <g>gur</g> leapannan</li>
          <li><m>gu an</m> taighean <en>to their houses</en> ≈ <g>gun</g> taighean</li>
          <li><m>gu am</m> baile <en>to their town</en> ≈ <g>gum</g> baile</li>
        </ul></p>
      <p>Note that these fused forms are often ambiguous and hence are probably best avoided in
        writing.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="pronoun">
      <h>prepositional pronouns</h>
      <p>Conjugated prepositions are used in place of <bad>gu mi</bad>, <bad>gu thu</bad>, ... ,
          <bad>gu iad</bad> – <ul>
          <li><m>thugam</m>
            <en>to me</en></li>
          <li><m>thugad</m>
            <en>to you</en></li>
          <li><m>thuice</m>
            <en>to her/it</en></li>
          <li><m>thuige</m>
            <en>to him/it</en></li>
          <li><m>thugainn</m>
            <en>to us</en></li>
          <li><m>thugaibh</m>
            <en>to you</en></li>
          <li><m>thuca</m>
            <en>to them</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Note that the following variants are also found – <g>chugam</g>, <g>chugad</g>,
          <g>chuice</g>, ... </p>
      <p>There are also emphatic forms (cf. <bad>gu mise</bad>, <bad>gu thuse</bad>, ... , <bad>gu
          iadsan</bad>) – <ul>
          <li><m>thugamsa</m>
            <en>to <emph>me</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>thugadsa</m>
            <en>to <emph>you</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>thuicese</m>
            <en>to <emph>her/it</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>thuigesan</m>
            <en>to <emph>him/it</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>thugainne</m>
            <en>to <emph>us</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>thugaibhse</m>
            <en>to <emph>you</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>thucasan</m>
            <en>to <emph>them</emph></en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Note that the form <g>thuigesan</g> breaks the ‘slender-to-slender, broad-to-broad’
        spelling rule, and hence is sometimes found written with a hyphen – <g>thuige-san</g>.</p>
      <p>Finally, there are also reflexive forms (cf. <bad>gu mi fhìn</bad>, <bad>gu thu
        fhèin</bad>, ... , <bad>gu iad fhèin</bad>) – <ul>
          <li><m>thugam fhèin / fhìn</m>
            <en>to myself</en></li>
          <li><m>thugad fhèin</m>
            <en>to yourself</en></li>
          <li><m>thuice fhèin</m>
            <en>to herself/itself</en></li>
          <li><m>thuige fhèin</m>
            <en>to himself/itself</en></li>
          <li><m>thugainn fhèin / fhìn</m>
            <en>to ourselves</en></li>
          <li><m>thugaibh fhèin</m>
            <en>to yourself</en></li>
          <li><m>thuca fhèin</m>
            <en>to themselves</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h>dependents</h>
    <section id="comp">
      <h>complement</h>
      <p>Some examples – <ul>
          <li>older pedagogical examples – <xl id="comp-older-pedag">
              <li>
                <gd>Tha mo mhàthair a’ sgrìobhadh litreach <m>gu m’athair</m> a tha air falbh.</gd>
                <tr>My mother is writing a letter to my father who is away.</tr>
                <ref text="621">td. 5</ref>
              </li>
              <li>
                <gd>Bha an latha brèagha blàth is thug an athair leis Iain agus Anna anns a’ chàr.
                  Chaidh iad sìos taobh an locha is stad iad aig àite bòidheach gorm. Chuir iad an
                  càr a stigh <m>gu taobh an rathaid</m> is thug iad brat a mach as a’ chàr air son
                  suidhe air. [...]</gd>
                <tr>The day was lovely and warm and their father took John and Ann in the car. They
                  went down the side of the lake and they stopped at a beautiful green place. They
                  put the car into the side of the road and they took a blanket out of the car for
                  sitting on. [...]</tr>
                <ref text="621">td. 6</ref>
              </li>
            </xl>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h>uses</h>
    <section id="uses-comp">
      <h>complement</h>
      <section>
        <h>verb</h>
        <p><g>gu</g> can be used to introduce the complement of certain verbs – <ul>
            <li><g><a href="?gd=rach">rach</a> gu ...</g>
              <en>go to something/someone</en></li>
            <li><g><a href="?gd=sgrìobh">sgrìobh</a> gu ...</g>
              <en>write to someone</en></li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h>noun</h>
        <p><g>gu</g> can be used to introduce the complement of certain nouns – <ul>
            <li><g><a href="?gd=litir">litir</a> gu</g>
              <en>a letter to/for someone</en></li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h>adverb</h>
        <p><g>gu</g> can be used to introduce the complement of certain pseudo-prepositions – <ul>
            <li><g><a href="?gd=a-staigh">a-staigh</a> gu</g>
              <en>inside (to)</en></li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </section>
    </section>
  </section>


